            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Nefza (formerly Djebel Abiod / Ǧabal Abyaḏ̣) is a small town in the North West Tunisian governorate of Béja, located in a valley between the Kroumir and the Mogod mountains. The Sidi el Barrak (Sīdi l-Baṛṛāg) Dam which is situated next to Nefza supplies water for different parts of the country. Beside its breath-taking arboreous nature, the Nefza region is famous for the kaki fruit called <hi rendition="#i">krīma</hi>, which is the town’s symbol as well.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Nefza, however this dialect as well as the dialects of the surrounding villages like e.g. Umm l-ʕBīd, Ḥbǟba and Ṭwīla are linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
